        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Keyword gap analysis</strong> is an SEO research process that compares your site's keyword rankings against one or more competitors to identify queries where competitors rank in the top 10 but your site doesn't appear or ranks below position 20. The resulting list of gap keywords represents missed organic traffic opportunities — content your competitors are monetising that you're not yet competing for.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary tools</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Ahrefs, Semrush</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Keyword Research</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Run frequency</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Quarterly</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">A competitor ranking for 2,000 keywords you don't target isn't a coincidence — it's a content roadmap. Keyword gap analysis systematically surfaces that roadmap and helps you prioritise which gaps to close first based on search volume, difficulty, and business relevance.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is keyword gap analysis?</h2>
        <p>Keyword gap analysis is the process of comparing your domain's organic keyword portfolio against competitors to surface queries you're missing. It answers the core question: "What is my competitor ranking for that I'm not, and why?"</p>
        <p>The output is typically a prioritised list of keywords that fall into one of three categories:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Missing keywords</strong> — competitors rank top 20; you have no ranking at all. These require new content.</li>
          <li><strong>Weak keywords</strong> — you rank positions 21–50 for these queries while competitors rank 1–10. These require content improvement and link building.</li>
          <li><strong>Opportunity keywords</strong> — you rank 11–20 and are close to page 1. These are the fastest wins — a targeted optimisation push can move them.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The core insight</div>
          <p>Keyword gap analysis inverts the usual content planning process. Instead of brainstorming topics from scratch, you start with proven demand — queries that already have ranking competitors and known search volume — and reverse-engineer what content you need to create.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why keyword gap analysis matters for organic growth</h2>
        <p>Competitor-led keyword research consistently outperforms topic brainstorming for one reason: the demand is already validated. Here's why gap analysis belongs in every quarterly SEO cycle:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Reveals missed revenue.</strong> Every keyword a competitor ranks for and you don't represents traffic flowing to their site instead of yours. For commercial-intent queries, each gap is a lost customer acquisition opportunity.</li>
          <li><strong>Shortens content research time.</strong> Analysing 3–4 competitors simultaneously produces a keyword list that would take months to build from search tools alone.</li>
          <li><strong>Surfaces emerging topics early.</strong> If a competitor published 40 articles on a topic in Q1 and they're now ranking, that's a signal the topic is gaining traction — you can still enter the conversation.</li>
          <li><strong>Identifies underserved niches.</strong> Sometimes all competitors rank for the same broad terms and nobody owns the niche variations. These are your fastest ranking opportunities.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritises link-building targets.</strong> High-KD gap keywords tell you where to focus outreach — matching competitor backlink profiles for the specific pages that are outranking you.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How to run a keyword gap analysis — step by step</h2>
        <p>Running a gap analysis follows a repeatable six-step process:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Identify true competitors.</strong> SEO competitors aren't necessarily business competitors. Search your most important keywords and note which domains appear consistently in positions 1–5. These are your SERP competitors — the ones whose keyword portfolios actually matter.</li>
          <li><strong>Input domains into a gap tool.</strong> Use Semrush's Keyword Gap tool (Competitive Research → Keyword Gap) or Ahrefs' Content Gap (Site Explorer → Content Gap). Enter your domain plus 2–4 competitors.</li>
          <li><strong>Apply the right filter.</strong> Set the filter to show keywords where competitors rank in positions 1–20 and your domain either doesn't appear or ranks below position 20.</li>
          <li><strong>Export and enrich the data.</strong> Download the keyword list. Add columns for keyword difficulty, search volume, and your current position. Filter out branded terms and irrelevant queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritise gaps.</strong> Score each gap keyword by: search volume (higher = more traffic potential), KD (lower = faster win), and business relevance (closer to buyer intent = better ROI).</li>
          <li><strong>Map to content actions.</strong> For each priority gap, decide: create new page, update existing page, or redirect a thin page to a stronger one targeting the same query.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="types">Types of keyword gaps — and how to close each one</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
