        <h2 id="vs-related">Keyword gap analysis vs keyword research — what's the difference?</h2>
        <p>They serve different starting points in the content planning process.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Keyword gap analysis</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Starts from competitor rankings</li>
              <li>Demand already proven by competitors</li>
              <li>Best for finding what you're missing</li>
              <li>Reactive: catches up to the competitive landscape</li>
              <li>Run quarterly to track competitor moves</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Keyword research</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Starts from seed terms and audience intent</li>
              <li>Discovers demand before competitors do</li>
              <li>Best for building a full content strategy</li>
              <li>Proactive: identifies emerging opportunities</li>
              <li>Run at strategy inception, then refresh quarterly</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for keyword gap analysis</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Choose SERP competitors, not business competitors.</strong> The company you compete with for customers might not compete with you for search traffic. Run your seed keywords in Google and identify who actually appears for them.</li>
          <li><strong>Analyse 3–5 competitors minimum.</strong> One competitor's keyword portfolio is a sample. Three to five gives you the actual landscape of what ranks for your topic area.</li>
          <li><strong>Filter by intent before volume.</strong> A 5,000-search/month keyword with wrong intent (informational when you need transactional) is less valuable than a 400-search keyword with buyer intent.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritise near-miss keywords first.</strong> Positions 11–20 are the fastest wins. A focused optimisation sprint (on-page improvements + 2–3 links) often moves these to page 1 within 4–8 weeks.</li>
          <li><strong>Track gaps closed, not just gaps found.</strong> Build a tracker that marks each gap keyword as "content created," "optimised," or "ranking." This turns the analysis into an actionable backlog.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-run after every competitor content push.</strong> When a competitor publishes 20 articles in a month, run a fresh gap check. They've just signalled which topics they're betting on.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't chase every gap.</strong> Some gaps exist because the topic is low-value, off-brand, or has terrible conversion potential. Apply a relevance filter before adding keywords to your calendar.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — copying competitor content instead of filling gaps</div>
          <p>The goal is to fill keyword gaps with original, better-quality content — not to replicate what competitors wrote. Publishing a near-identical article to a competitor's already-ranking page rarely produces page-1 rankings. Study what they missed: what questions their article doesn't answer, what examples are absent, what depth is lacking. Fill those gaps within your own content.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common keyword gap analysis mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Using only one competitor</strong> — single-competitor analysis produces a partial picture. Always include at least 3 SERP competitors.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring keyword difficulty</strong> — a list of gap keywords without KD filtering leads to pursuing high-competition terms you can't win with your current authority.</li>
          <li><strong>Not filtering branded terms</strong> — competitors rank for their own brand names and product names. These gaps are not rankable for you. Filter them out before prioritising.</li>
          <li><strong>Running the analysis once and forgetting it</strong> — keyword gaps evolve monthly. A quarterly rhythm keeps the list current and catches new competitor moves.</li>
          <li><strong>Measuring success only by rankings</strong> — the end goal is traffic and conversions. A keyword closed from position 22 to position 12 is progress, but only a move to position 1–3 drives meaningful clicks.</li>
        </ul>

